The paper focuses on evaluating the quality of experience (QoE) of multimedia content using electroencephalography (EEG) and proposes a novel method using deep neural networks for improved modeling of EEG. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, which deals with the design, evaluation, and implementation of interactive computing systems for human use. 

The paper also uses deep neural networks for modeling EEG, which falls under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with the study and development of algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data. 

Furthermore, the paper aims to model spatio-temporal characteristics relevant for QoE analysis within learning models, which suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category, which deals with the study and development of algorithms inspired by the structure and function of the brain. 

The paper also mentions using deep neural networks for image processing, which suggests that it may belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category, which deals with the study and development of algorithms for analyzing and understanding visual data.
